## Copilot

I've drafted a comprehensive governance enhancement issue that systematically addresses excuse-based test dodging:

````yaml type="draft-issue"
type: draft-issue
tag: "excuse-deflection-ban-governance-enhancement"
issueNumber: 0
repository: "APGI-cmy/maturion-foreman-governance"
state: "draft"
title: "[GOVERNANCE] Ban Excuse-Based Test Dodging: Harden Ownership & Eliminate Nitpicking, Non-Blocking, and Similar Deferral Patterns Across All Agents"
description: |-
    # GOVERNANCE ENHANCEMENT PROPOSAL: Ban Excuse-Based Test Dodging ‚Äì Maximum Ownership, Zero Deferral Patterns, and Universal STOP-AND-FIX

    ## Executive Summary
    - **Objective**: Systematically ban all forms of excuse-based test dodging across governance feedback loops, code, infrastructure, and review, enforcing true 100% STOP-AND-FIX compliance. Agents must take action on any observed test debt or governance failure in their domain, and escalate any issue that cannot be directly resolved.
    - **Scope**: The ban covers (but is not limited to): "nitpicking", "non-blocking", "leftover from previous work", "not my assignment/domain", "yaml/config-only", "cosmetic only", "defer for later/future work", "unrelated to current PR", "outside scope/next time", "can't test here", "low-risk", "transient/flaky", "blocked by X", "reviewer dismissals" and any similar deflection.

    ## Detail

    ### Governance Doctrine and Rationale
    - 100% really means the entire codebase and all agent/infra domains unless a file is institutionally or contractually protected. Silently ignoring problems in protected files IS itself a governance violation if not escalated.
    - "If I see it, I own it. Fix it or escalate it. Silence is NOT compliance."
    - Agents MUST take action on ANY detected test, build, code, infrastructure, or policy problem they see‚Äîregardless of ownership.
    - All forms of subjective excuse, minimization of feedback, or deferral through language patterning are explicitly forbidden as governance anti-patterns.

    ### Examples of Banned Excuse Patterns
    - "That's just nitpicking" / "nitpick"
    - "Non-blocking / not critical"
    - "Leftover from previous work / found but not my fault"
    - "Not required for this ticket / not my assignment"
    - "Just a shell script/yaml/config change"
    - "Cosmetic only / style issue"
    - "Can be deferred / I'll fix it after merge / future work"
    - "Unrelated to this PR / outside scope"
    - "Current tests are sufficient / good enough"
    - "Can't reproduce / flaky / transient failure"
    - "Blocked by dependencies / infra / upstream"
    - "Reviewer said don't bother"
    - "No regression observed after workaround"
    - Any similar attempt to minimize, discharge, delay, or deflect fixing a real problem

    ### New Canonical Principle Proposal
    - **STOP-AND-FIX and zero test debt means absolutely all discovered issues must be fixed (or escalated if not directly fixable), regardless of agent, file type, severity, assignment, or context.**
    - Any agent who sees a problem, even outside their authority, is responsible to file an escalation‚Äîthey must NOT ignore, minimize, or hide it.
    - The use of any recognized anti-pattern of excuse (see above examples), in code, review comments, escalation notes, PREHANDOVER_PROOF, or documentation, is itself a governance violation subject to escalation and, on repetition, enforcement.
    - ALL reviewer feedback is in-scope for fix unless the reviewer EXPLICITLY grants an exception via "non-blocking (optional)" and the PREHANDOVER_PROOF records it.

    ### Enforcement Mechanisms
    - Update STOP-AND-FIX and PR Gating canons to ban excuse/deferral patterns explicitly
    - Add section "Recognized Test Dodging Excuse Patterns" to canon, listing all above examples
    - Require all agent contracts, reviews, and scripts to include an "escalation obligation" for faults observed but not directly actionable
    - Precedent stories and Bootstrap Learnings (BL) to be created for postmortems on any discovered test dodging via excuse language
    - Continuous compliance auditing on this ban, with metrics on trending excuse patterns

    ### Bootstrap Learning
    - Add BL-TEST-DODGING-EXCUSE-VECTORS to learning canon, enumerating patterns observed in historical review and test regimes
    - Link to high-profile test debt/test dodging incidents in history (e.g., PR #212/213 PartPulse, earlier reviews, failed builds, repeated merge-of-shame events)

    ### Next Actions
    1. Major update to STOP_AND_FIX_DOCTRINE.md; clarify NO excuses, total visible codebase ownership, escalation required for protected/file boundaries.
    2. Update Test Debt Canon and PR Gate protocol to match new anti-deflection requirements.
    3. Add cross-references to Bootstrap Learning and governance anti-pattern catalog.
    4. Optionally, establish single-click escalation triggers for agents finding faults outside agent scope.
    5. Community review, CS2 approval, then ratify into canon.

    ---
    **Assignee:** APGI-cmy, governance-repo-administrator
    **Labels:** governance, enhancement, STOP-AND-FIX, test-debt, test-dodging, learning, anti-pattern
assignees: ["APGI-cmy", "governance-repo-administrator"]
labels: ["governance", "enhancement", "STOP-AND-FIX", "test-debt", "test-dodging", "learning", "anti-pattern"]
````

